e cattle business. About 10 years ago I found myself in Greenwich New York for about a month buying replacement dairy heifers to send back home. As Greenwich is on the Vermont border, I spent my spare time touring New England and upstate New York looking for Antiques. The thing that caught my eye the most were the beautifully ornate cast iron kitchen ranges. We had nothing like that back home and I had to have one. One long weekend, I travelled all the way over to Maine and bought a Quaker Jewel.It would be shipped to me after restoration.\r\n \r\nAfter about five more years in the business of buying and selling livestock, I was trying to figure out a less stressfull way to make a living. I came up with a plan. I felt the antique stoves and ranges of the North East should sell well in the vacation homes of the western mountains. I tried it and it has been successful.I restore them in the traditional black and also have developed an antiquing technique in different colors of high heat paint. I also do the enamel ranges of the art deco style.I now make two trips a year with a large trailer to the Northeast for loads of unrestored stoves and ranges. I not only sell them in the southwest, but  deliver my restored stoves all the way back to New England.\r\n \r\nOf course, room would prohibit nearly anyone from having a large collection of  kitchen ranges,but I have saved some , and of course I still have my original Quaker Jewel.It is perhaps more satisfying to restore one, and sell it to somebody who will love and admire it as much as you, then to keep a collection in a barn for just yourself to look at.With the travel, meeting interesting new friends, and many satisfied customers, I can\'t think of a better Job.\r\n ','antique stoves',0,0,'','',0,NULL,'a:3:{s:8:\"show_age\";b:1;s:6:\"msg_on\";b:1;s:11:\"invite_only\";b:0;}','a:3:{s:7:\"comment\";b:1;s:5:\"buddy\";b:1;s:7:\"message\";b:1;}','2010-02-11 10:43:59','2009-05-15 12:39:11'),(1230,1250,'casual','1976-01-17','f